## Finding: "Compliance as a Ghost" — GDPR/SOC2/HIPAA/ISO27001 Appears in 7 of 11 Targets with No Cross-Phase Owner

### Gap Type: MISSING_HANDOFF
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence:
Compliance appears as an isolated finding in T0 (no compliance posture baseline), T1 (no compliance-aware brainstorming), T2 (data flow and privacy design absent), T3 (no GDPR data handling patterns), T4 (financial_compliance skill exists but GDPR/HIPAA/ISO27001 absent), T5 (legal_compliance skill is surface-level boilerplate), T6 (no evidence that compliance artifacts are handed off), and T7 (no compliance maintenance cycle). Compliance is treated as a Phase 4 audit checklist item rather than a cross-lifecycle program. There is NO skill, agent, command, or workflow that owns the compliance PROGRAM — meaning: data classification done in Phase 2 design is never verified in Phase 4, legal pages created in Phase 5.75 are never linked back to actual data handling decisions made in Phase 3, and Phase 7 maintenance has no compliance drift detection mechanism whatsoever.

The pattern: each phase dismisses compliance as "handled elsewhere" and no phase actually owns it end-to-end. The result is a compliance gap that exists in the dark matter BETWEEN every phase transition.

### Proposed Resolution: Framework-level compliance program infrastructure: a `compliance_program` skill (cross-phase) plus a `compliance-reviewer` agent that runs at Phase 2→3 gate, Phase 4→5 gate, and Phase 7 continuously. Also a `/compliance-audit` command.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Affects ALL 11 phases. A single compliance failure post-launch can shut down the product. GDPR violations carry up to 4% global annual turnover fines. SOC2 failures can terminate enterprise contracts.

