## Finding: "Internationalization Is Invisible" — i18n/l10n Has Zero Coverage Across the Entire Framework

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence:
After reading all 11 gaps.logs and the full framework, there is NO mention of internationalization (i18n) or localization (l10n) in ANY phase, ANY skill, ANY agent, ANY command, or ANY workflow. This is a systemic absence, not a phase-specific one.

A world-class software development lifecycle framework must address i18n at minimum in:
- Phase 1 (Brainstorm): Market scope decision — will this product serve non-English markets?
- Phase 2 (Design): i18n architecture — string externalization strategy, locale-aware data models (dates, currencies, addresses), RTL layout considerations
- Phase 3 (Build): String extraction patterns, i18n-safe component design, locale-aware formatting
- Phase 4 (Secure): Locale-specific XSS vectors (encoding differences), character set injection attacks
- Phase 5 (Ship): Locale-aware CI/CD (build per locale? single build with runtime locale?)
- Phase 6 (Handoff): Translation workflow handoff, locale QA checklist
- Phase 7 (Maintenance): Translation maintenance, new string tracking, locale regression testing

The impact: any framework-guided project targeting an international market starts i18n from scratch with no guidance. This is particularly painful because retrofitting i18n into an existing codebase is 3-5x more expensive than building it in from the start.

### Proposed Resolution: New skill `internationalization_design` (Phase 2) covering i18n architecture decisions. New skill `i18n_implementation` (Phase 3) covering string externalization, locale-safe formatting, RTL. Add i18n checklist section to Phase 5.75 Beta and Phase 6 Handoff. Priority: P1 given cost of retrofitting.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Any project that discovers it needs i18n in Phase 5 or later faces a full architectural retrofit. Without Phase 2 guidance, teams make locale-hostile data model decisions (storing dates without timezone, currency as float without locale, addresses in single-field format).

