## Finding: "Disaster Recovery Is a One-Time Handoff Document, Not a Living Practice"

### Gap Type: MISSING_HANDOFF
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence:
`disaster_recovery` skill lives in Phase 6 (Handoff). This placement encodes a critical mental model error: DR is treated as a one-time setup artifact created at handoff, not an ongoing operational discipline that must be designed in Phase 2, tested in Phase 4, exercised in Phase 5.5, and continuously practiced in Phase 7.

The complete DR lifecycle that the framework currently has no single path through:
- Phase 2: RTO/RPO requirements capture (what is the acceptable recovery time and data loss?)
- Phase 3: DR-aware architecture (no single points of failure, circuit breakers, graceful degradation)
- Phase 4: DR testing (chaos engineering, failover tests, backup restore verification)
- Phase 5: DR-aware deployment (blue/green enables instant rollback; canary limits blast radius)
- Phase 5.5 Alpha: Backup strategy verified (backup_strategy skill exists — good)
- Phase 6: DR runbooks created (disaster_recovery skill — good but orphaned)
- Phase 7: DR exercises (scheduled chaos tests, tabletop exercises, postmortem-driven DR improvements)

The T7 analysis found no incident response operations skill. The T55 analysis found backup strategy but no restore testing verification loop. The T6 analysis found a DR skill but no DR test cadence. These are all fragments of the same systemic absence: DR as an operational program.

### Proposed Resolution: (1) Move `disaster_recovery` skill to be Phase 2→7 referenced, not Phase 6 only. (2) New `chaos_engineering` skill (Phase 4/7). (3) New `dr_exercise_cadence` section in Phase 7. (4) Add RTO/RPO requirements to Phase 2 design templates.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Every phase that skips DR design contributes to a system where recovery time is unknown until a disaster occurs. Mean Time To Recover (MTTR) has no framework-level ownership.

